WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.260 --> 00:00:01.260
Martha Stewart @Google
November 4, 2011

00:00:01.260 --> 00:00:02.260
&gt;&gt;Marissa Mayer: Good morning.

00:00:02.260 --> 00:00:04.440
Today, we have with us Martha Stewart.

00:00:04.440 --> 00:00:12.000
[ Cheers and applause ]
&gt;&gt;Marissa Mayer: And Martha's stats are really

00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:13.000
impressive.

00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:15.120
We think a lot about stats and data here at
Google.

00:00:15.120 --> 00:00:16.510
But these are pretty amazing.

00:00:16.510 --> 00:00:21.330
37 million readers, users, viewers, and listeners
each month.

00:00:21.330 --> 00:00:27.230
She inspires them to celebrate art in their
everyday living through cooking, gardening,

00:00:27.230 --> 00:00:32.470
entertaining, organizing their holidays, pets,
their entire lifestyle.

00:00:32.470 --> 00:00:36.280
Today we're here to look at her most personal
book yet.

00:00:36.280 --> 00:00:41.039
She literally invites readers into her home
for a year's worth of celebrations across

00:00:41.039 --> 00:00:43.780
all times of day and all seasons.

00:00:43.780 --> 00:00:50.420
This book is a return to her first book, "Entertaining,"
which actually established Martha as a household

00:00:50.420 --> 00:00:53.280
name more than 30 years ago.

00:00:53.280 --> 00:00:56.749
And this is her 75th book.

00:00:56.749 --> 00:01:03.549
I heard that on Jay Leno, and I thought it
was a joke, but it is actually her 75th book.

00:01:03.549 --> 00:01:08.420
1800 recipes each year in her magazines, properties,
and Martha Stewart Show.

00:01:08.420 --> 00:01:11.970
And she's also won 18 Emmys.

00:01:11.970 --> 00:01:18.150
And proximate to our industry, she's also
won the Webby for the best lifestyle Web site.

00:01:18.150 --> 00:01:20.620
Please welcome Martha Stewart.

00:01:20.620 --> 00:01:26.890
[ Cheers and applause ]
&gt;&gt;Martha Stewart: Hello.

00:01:26.890 --> 00:01:28.970
Hi, everybody.

00:01:28.970 --> 00:01:32.110
Thank you, Marissa.

00:01:32.110 --> 00:01:38.130
&gt;&gt;Marissa Mayer: We are so delighted to have
you here.

00:01:38.130 --> 00:01:39.640
&gt;&gt;Martha Stewart: I just tweeted.

00:01:39.640 --> 00:01:41.090
[ Laughter ]
&gt;&gt;Marissa Mayer: That's great.

00:01:41.090 --> 00:01:43.710
We're so excited here -- to have you here
today.

00:01:43.710 --> 00:01:48.010
You can see the Googlers are all so excited
that you have made the trip to come and see

00:01:48.010 --> 00:01:50.790
us here in Mountain View.

00:01:50.790 --> 00:01:55.140
And I'm going to ask you a few questions,
we have a lot of questions from the audience

00:01:55.140 --> 00:01:59.000
later, we've also been collecting questions
ahead of time, and actually, the first one

00:01:59.000 --> 00:02:01.670
was a bit of a joke from Ted Prodromou.

00:02:01.670 --> 00:02:06.780
He asked, do you have any suggestions for
decorating Charlie's Cafe, which is the room

00:02:06.780 --> 00:02:07.780
that we're in.

00:02:07.780 --> 00:02:10.709
&gt;&gt;Martha Stewart: The flowers are very fancy
for Charlie's Cafe.

00:02:10.709 --> 00:02:12.859
[ Laughter ]
&gt;&gt;Marissa Mayer: Thank you.

00:02:12.859 --> 00:02:15.010
&gt;&gt;Martha Stewart: They are beautiful.

00:02:15.010 --> 00:02:17.909
Succulents and ORCHIDS and roses.

00:02:17.909 --> 00:02:19.659
Very beautiful.

00:02:19.659 --> 00:02:23.150
No, you can't decorate a place like this.

00:02:23.150 --> 00:02:28.150
[ Laughter ]
&gt;&gt;Martha Stewart: It's already the place.

00:02:28.150 --> 00:02:29.400
And it's so exciting to be here.

00:02:29.400 --> 00:02:30.400
I'm really happy.

00:02:30.400 --> 00:02:31.400
Thank you.

00:02:31.400 --> 00:02:33.749
&gt;&gt;Marissa Mayer: It's a very functional space,
if not a very decorated space.

00:02:33.749 --> 00:02:38.819
But I what I wanted to go ahead and start
off with is where you started.

00:02:38.819 --> 00:02:43.319
Because I think what a lot of people don't
know and I was surprised, I got to visit your

00:02:43.319 --> 00:02:48.360
office and your studio last year, is that
you actually started off as a model.

00:02:48.360 --> 00:02:49.360
&gt;&gt;Martha Stewart: I did.

00:02:49.360 --> 00:02:50.360
&gt;&gt;Marissa Mayer: A world-renowned model.

00:02:50.360 --> 00:02:51.609
We actually have this beautiful photo of Martha
when she was a model.

00:02:51.609 --> 00:02:52.609
(Whistles).

00:02:52.609 --> 00:02:58.950
&gt;&gt;Marissa Mayer: And, of course, we also have
the Google Image search.

00:02:58.950 --> 00:03:04.400
If you type in "Martha Stewart model," you
can see all of her model shots.

00:03:04.400 --> 00:03:05.939
&gt;&gt;Martha Stewart: Oh, look.

00:03:05.939 --> 00:03:07.970
Where that did that waist go?

00:03:07.970 --> 00:03:12.090
&gt;&gt;Marissa Mayer: Just stunningly beautiful.

00:03:12.090 --> 00:03:17.200
I guess I would love to hear the story of
how you went from a model to becoming a do-it-yourself

00:03:17.200 --> 00:03:20.319
icon and how you --
&gt;&gt;Martha Stewart: Well, before I was a model,

00:03:20.319 --> 00:03:21.939
I was actually a student.

00:03:21.939 --> 00:03:22.939
&gt;&gt;Marissa Mayer: Okay.

00:03:22.939 --> 00:03:28.170
&gt;&gt;Martha Stewart: And during high school,
in order -- one of six kids, my father was

00:03:28.170 --> 00:03:33.200
a pharmaceutical salesman, and my mother was
a teacher, sixth-grade teacher.

00:03:33.200 --> 00:03:36.859
And there was no extra money to go to college.

00:03:36.859 --> 00:03:39.400
There was no extra money to buy beautiful
clothes.

00:03:39.400 --> 00:03:41.000
And I loved beautiful clothes.

00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:44.549
My mother was quite well dressed, but she
made everything.

00:03:44.549 --> 00:03:49.159
So we learned how to sew, we learned how to
do all those homely things at home.

00:03:49.159 --> 00:03:56.260
So I started modeling when I was 13 to pay
for extras, like college.

00:03:56.260 --> 00:04:03.799
And it was very successful, because in those
days, college was only $3500 a year, including

00:04:03.799 --> 00:04:04.870
room and board.

00:04:04.870 --> 00:04:10.299
And that's very cheap compared to what it
is now, $55,000, 75,000, whatever.

00:04:10.299 --> 00:04:16.320
So I did commercials, television commercials,
and I did print ads and print editorial.

00:04:16.320 --> 00:04:24.560
And it was a lot of fun, and it paid $50 an
hour at that time, which was a lot of money.

00:04:24.560 --> 00:04:30.140
And my commercials appeared on things like
"Gunsmoke" and "Wyatt Earp" and different

00:04:30.140 --> 00:04:34.350
-- So it was a very, very good way to earn
money.

00:04:34.350 --> 00:04:38.490
So it wasn't really -- and all during college,
too, I went to Barnard college at Columbia

00:04:38.490 --> 00:04:41.190
University, and at that time, too, I was modeling.

00:04:41.190 --> 00:04:44.520
&gt;&gt;Marissa Mayer: How did you make the transition
from model to, you know --

00:04:44.520 --> 00:04:45.520
&gt;&gt;Martha Stewart: To whatever?

00:04:45.520 --> 00:04:50.290
&gt;&gt;Marissa Mayer: I mean, your own show and
to being really a do-it-yourself icon.

00:04:50.290 --> 00:04:54.590
&gt;&gt;Martha Stewart: After college and during
college, I was -- my father-in-law happened

00:04:54.590 --> 00:04:55.890
to be a stockbroker.

00:04:55.890 --> 00:04:57.690
He owned a seat on the New York Stock Exchange.

00:04:57.690 --> 00:05:00.850
And I got interested in investing.

00:05:00.850 --> 00:05:07.460
It was as interesting then, really, as it
is now, although the money wasn't as great.

00:05:07.460 --> 00:05:12.350
But you could, if you invested in McDonald's,
for example, in the early days, it was -- that

00:05:12.350 --> 00:05:14.580
was one of the most successful investments.

00:05:14.580 --> 00:05:19.040
Or in a thing like -- it was called Leasco
Data Processing, a very good investment if

00:05:19.040 --> 00:05:25.570
you bought warrants, on warrants, and you
invested kind of crazily like my little firm

00:05:25.570 --> 00:05:26.590
that I belonged to.

00:05:26.590 --> 00:05:31.900
I became a stockbroker right after college
because I thought that would be an interesting

00:05:31.900 --> 00:05:33.380
way to learn about business.

00:05:33.380 --> 00:05:39.490
And it was, because I learned about how a
good company or even a bad company functioned.

00:05:39.490 --> 00:05:42.290
But this was before big-time technology.

00:05:42.290 --> 00:05:47.730
And I gave up the stock market after about
an eight-year career, which was -- which I

00:05:47.730 --> 00:05:49.390
loved very much.

00:05:49.390 --> 00:05:50.990
And I started a catering business.

00:05:50.990 --> 00:05:54.440
The catering is what led me into the lifestyle
business.

00:05:54.440 --> 00:05:56.730
And the writing of my first book in 1982.

00:05:56.730 --> 00:06:00.880
&gt;&gt;Marissa Mayer: How did Martha Stewart Living
Omnimedia get started.

00:06:00.880 --> 00:06:07.120
&gt;&gt;Martha Stewart: Well, I wanted to -- I had
so many ideas for lifestyle, and I realized

00:06:07.120 --> 00:06:11.560
that there were voids in the media world.

00:06:11.560 --> 00:06:21.170
There was no one book, for example, like "Entertaining"
that would teach you really the basic tenets

00:06:21.170 --> 00:06:24.330
of good home entertaining.

00:06:24.330 --> 00:06:26.550
There was no great garden book.

00:06:26.550 --> 00:06:29.520
And these are illustrated books.

00:06:29.520 --> 00:06:30.650
I loved photography.

00:06:30.650 --> 00:06:34.280
I loved colored photography especially.

00:06:34.280 --> 00:06:38.390
And so I went to my publisher and I said,
"I'd like to do a whole series of beautiful

00:06:38.390 --> 00:06:43.020
how-to books so people could really learn
how to do everything."

00:06:43.020 --> 00:06:48.110
And they said, "Eh, it's all right, but, you
know, you just keep writing your book a year."

00:06:48.110 --> 00:06:49.990
And I was writing a book a year.

00:06:49.990 --> 00:06:56.740
So then I went to Sy Newhouse, who is the
head of Conde Nast Publishing, and he said,

00:06:56.740 --> 00:06:59.510
"Well, that sounds like a magazine."

00:06:59.510 --> 00:07:05.290
And so I gave him a proposal for a magazine,
and then it went on from there.

00:07:05.290 --> 00:07:12.110
So I started Martha Stewart Living, the magazine,
not with Conde Nast, but with Time Warner,

00:07:12.110 --> 00:07:13.550
in 1990.

00:07:13.550 --> 00:07:21.790
And from there, everything else has grown,
especially the idea of synergy between media,

00:07:21.790 --> 00:07:25.640
television, bringing all the -- all kinds
of media together.

00:07:25.640 --> 00:07:28.330
And then, of course, Internet, and then merchandising.

00:07:28.330 --> 00:07:32.120
&gt;&gt;Marissa Mayer: You can see the whole array
of different magazines.

00:07:32.120 --> 00:07:33.640
That probably isn't even all of them.

00:07:33.640 --> 00:07:36.699
&gt;&gt;Martha Stewart: Yeah, you're missing Everyday
Food magazine, our smaller magazine there.

00:07:36.699 --> 00:07:40.740
[ Laughter ]
&gt;&gt;Marissa Mayer: So what were the early days

00:07:40.740 --> 00:07:42.360
at Martha Stewart Living like?

00:07:42.360 --> 00:07:43.950
&gt;&gt;Martha Stewart: Well, it was so much fun.

00:07:43.950 --> 00:07:50.700
We were -- we consider ourselves a microcosm
of a big media company, Time Warner.

00:07:50.700 --> 00:07:52.700
And we were very proud of being that microcosm.

00:07:52.700 --> 00:07:58.150
We were put on the most unfriendly floor in
the time -- in the Time Warner Tower on Sixth

00:07:58.150 --> 00:07:59.340
Avenue.

00:07:59.340 --> 00:08:03.460
Below us was all the mechanics of the building.

00:08:03.460 --> 00:08:09.400
So my feet were warm because it was a hot
floor, and probably an unhealthy floor.

00:08:09.400 --> 00:08:10.460
I hated it.

00:08:10.460 --> 00:08:12.770
The windows didn't open.

00:08:12.770 --> 00:08:16.360
We were on the, like, fifty something floor
and you wouldn't want your windows to open

00:08:16.360 --> 00:08:18.110
up there.

00:08:18.110 --> 00:08:21.210
It was unhealthy in that respect.

00:08:21.210 --> 00:08:22.770
No fresh air.

00:08:22.770 --> 00:08:24.400
Hermetically sealed.

00:08:24.400 --> 00:08:29.490
And ever since that little time, I stayed
in that office for about a year and a half,

00:08:29.490 --> 00:08:31.139
and I begged to move.

00:08:31.139 --> 00:08:35.580
And we found a space that, -- with windows
that opened, with fresh air, with natural

00:08:35.580 --> 00:08:38.330
gas for the stoves for our kitchens.

00:08:38.330 --> 00:08:41.540
All of that meant a lot for me, sunlight,
daylight.

00:08:41.540 --> 00:08:43.440
It was very important.

00:08:43.440 --> 00:08:45.830
And ever since then, we've -- and you've been
to our office.

00:08:45.830 --> 00:08:50.480
And you know that we have sunlight and daylight,
much like you have out here, all much smaller.

00:08:50.480 --> 00:08:53.130
&gt;&gt;Marissa Mayer: Well, you're here in Silicon
Valley.

00:08:53.130 --> 00:08:55.150
And it's the heart of innovation.

00:08:55.150 --> 00:08:59.110
And you're one of the few people in the world
who has actually defined an industry.

00:08:59.110 --> 00:09:04.870
So what words of advice do you have for young
entrepreneurs as to how they might try and

00:09:04.870 --> 00:09:05.870
do the same?

00:09:05.870 --> 00:09:11.410
We have a lot of people here who are entrepreneurs
within Google and trying to build new businesses.

00:09:11.410 --> 00:09:17.990
&gt;&gt;Martha Stewart: Again, it's finding a void,
I think, in your area of interest and expertise,

00:09:17.990 --> 00:09:25.000
finding that void that other people really
also consider a void, and building in that

00:09:25.000 --> 00:09:32.050
void something that is so original and so
enticing and so desirable that many other

00:09:32.050 --> 00:09:34.430
people will have to come there.

00:09:34.430 --> 00:09:37.840
I mean, -- well, that's what Google is.

00:09:37.840 --> 00:09:39.360
Had you to come to Google.

00:09:39.360 --> 00:09:41.010
There was no choice.

00:09:41.010 --> 00:09:42.380
There was no other way.

00:09:42.380 --> 00:09:47.750
There were other companies, but it was by
far the most interesting place to go.

00:09:47.750 --> 00:09:54.070
I was an early adapter or adopter of technology,
and I bought my first computer -- it doesn't

00:09:54.070 --> 00:10:00.030
sound like very long ago -- but 1982, I bought
my first IBM computer, a PC.

00:10:00.030 --> 00:10:01.089
I still have it.

00:10:01.089 --> 00:10:04.580
[ Laughter ]
&gt;&gt;Martha Stewart: I haven't plugged it in.

00:10:04.580 --> 00:10:06.420
I don't even -- I haven't even tried.

00:10:06.420 --> 00:10:10.210
But I still have it, that silly-looking little
thing.

00:10:10.210 --> 00:10:13.810
But it was so interesting what was going on.

00:10:13.810 --> 00:10:15.840
And I've tried to keep up.

00:10:15.840 --> 00:10:18.000
I know there's lots I don't know.

00:10:18.000 --> 00:10:23.090
But as much as I can, I keep up with the newest.

00:10:23.090 --> 00:10:30.390
And I watch with interest the new IPOs that
are happening, like the Groupon this morning.

00:10:30.390 --> 00:10:35.680
And testing the waters for what else we are
going to be distracted with in our quest for

00:10:35.680 --> 00:10:38.880
our own particular interests; right?

00:10:38.880 --> 00:10:42.130
There's a lot of distracting stuff out there,
Marissa, really.

00:10:42.130 --> 00:10:46.540
&gt;&gt;Marissa Mayer: It's interesting, we're about
a half a mile down the road from the Computer

00:10:46.540 --> 00:10:50.250
History Museum, which always to me seems like
a oxymoron, because it's such a short history.

00:10:50.250 --> 00:10:52.620
It's really amazing to see --
&gt;&gt;Martha Stewart: Oh, it is.

00:10:52.620 --> 00:10:55.290
It's like a fragment of time.

00:10:55.290 --> 00:11:00.380
&gt;&gt;Marissa Mayer: So what are the three -- if
you had to name three really important lessons

00:11:00.380 --> 00:11:04.520
that you've learned throughout evolving your
business, you've been so successful, what

00:11:04.520 --> 00:11:06.150
are three of the most important lessons?

00:11:06.150 --> 00:11:11.730
&gt;&gt;Martha Stewart: Well, finding that niche
that interests you and will interest others,

00:11:11.730 --> 00:11:16.591
that's one very, very -- and a niche -- a
niche can be as big as the Grand Canyon, you

00:11:16.591 --> 00:11:17.770
know?

00:11:17.770 --> 00:11:19.960
It doesn't have to be a tiny little space.

00:11:19.960 --> 00:11:22.420
It can be a giant space.

00:11:22.420 --> 00:11:30.970
And then creating content or something to
fill that cavern or canyon with something

00:11:30.970 --> 00:11:34.470
really valuable and well-made.

00:11:34.470 --> 00:11:38.520
And it can be pretty, too, like your beautiful
Google Maps.

00:11:38.520 --> 00:11:44.690
Like your -- and like so many things that
you find on the Internet that are appealing

00:11:44.690 --> 00:11:47.590
to the eye but are understandable at the same
time.

00:11:47.590 --> 00:11:50.180
And then, third, just continue with it.

00:11:50.180 --> 00:11:52.800
And don't forget to look elsewhere.

00:11:52.800 --> 00:11:57.530
Don't forget to look at what's coming up behind
you, what's coming in front of you.

00:11:57.530 --> 00:12:00.310
Always keeping as current as possible.

00:12:00.310 --> 00:12:01.660
Okay.

00:12:01.660 --> 00:12:03.899
And you have so much variety in your business.

00:12:03.899 --> 00:12:07.950
You know, there's cooking, there's crafting,
there's organizing, there's weddings, blogging,

00:12:07.950 --> 00:12:11.630
there's tweeting, there's the TV show, there's
the radio show.

00:12:11.630 --> 00:12:14.060
How do you decide to go into a new area?

00:12:14.060 --> 00:12:16.480
How do you decide to explore a new venture?

00:12:16.480 --> 00:12:22.470
&gt;&gt;Martha Stewart: Well, we were very Avid
explorers in all kinds of media from the first

00:12:22.470 --> 00:12:23.750
place.

00:12:23.750 --> 00:12:30.050
We were also very Avid in exploring retail
business -- merchandising businesses.

00:12:30.050 --> 00:12:35.370
And we continue to be so, although we now
know that you cannot, even as a corporation,

00:12:35.370 --> 00:12:39.430
do every single thing that you want to do.

00:12:39.430 --> 00:12:47.120
And you must concentrate on those areas that
are really the most profitable, the most interesting,

00:12:47.120 --> 00:12:50.710
the most -- have the most future, have the
most growth potential.

00:12:50.710 --> 00:12:56.210
So that's what we're doing now, is figuring
out, with our company, our small company,

00:12:56.210 --> 00:12:59.730
what really we should be focusing on.

00:12:59.730 --> 00:13:00.960
&gt;&gt;Marissa Mayer: Okay.

00:13:00.960 --> 00:13:03.180
Well, we have a little video I'd like to show.

00:13:03.180 --> 00:13:08.140
Because one of the things we've seen is that
users are constantly Googling you.

00:13:08.140 --> 00:13:13.550
They're constantly Googling you, your recipes,
the crafts, your products.

00:13:13.550 --> 00:13:18.580
You can see there's so much inspiration.

00:13:18.580 --> 00:13:23.990
And you've gone to great lengths to make all
of your content really accessible online.

00:13:23.990 --> 00:13:25.490
&gt;&gt;Martha Stewart: Yes, we have.

00:13:25.490 --> 00:13:30.529
&gt;&gt;Marissa Mayer: And I guess I'd like to --
&gt;&gt;Martha Stewart: Have you made a croquembouche?

00:13:30.529 --> 00:13:36.440
&gt;&gt;Marissa Mayer: Unfortunately, I can't really
cook, but my husband is a fabulous cook.

00:13:36.440 --> 00:13:41.030
So, --
&gt;&gt;Martha Stewart: Do you embroider?

00:13:41.030 --> 00:13:42.190
&gt;&gt;Marissa Mayer: I do embroider.

00:13:42.190 --> 00:13:43.190
I do.

00:13:43.190 --> 00:13:44.630
I do, especially cross stitch.

00:13:44.630 --> 00:13:49.580
I do like to sew, and I like to do crafts
with LEDs.

00:13:49.580 --> 00:13:53.100
But -- so I like to do, like, light displays
and things.

00:13:53.100 --> 00:13:57.000
But people have, obviously, been so inspired
by what you have done.

00:13:57.000 --> 00:14:01.399
Part of it is that you have made so much of
what you do really accessible to them through

00:14:01.399 --> 00:14:02.399
the Internet.

00:14:02.399 --> 00:14:06.820
So I thought I -- I'd like you to talk a little
bit about how the Internet has changed your

00:14:06.820 --> 00:14:09.890
business, how it's made you more accessible
to users?

00:14:09.890 --> 00:14:12.870
&gt;&gt;Martha Stewart: Well, it's changed it tremendously.

00:14:12.870 --> 00:14:16.910
And we want to be where our customers need
and want us.

00:14:16.910 --> 00:14:22.260
And more and more of our customers really
do want us on the Internet.

00:14:22.260 --> 00:14:30.250
As the population of tablet owners grows,
we were very aware of that, and we wanted

00:14:30.250 --> 00:14:32.890
